 The Ministry of Health on Friday announced that 2,444 people tested positive for COVID-19 from a sample size of 9,269 tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 26.4%. The total confirmed positive cases are now 309,130 while the cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,065,623. "From the cases, 2,298 are Kenyans while 146 are foreigners; 1,322 are females and 1,122 are males. The youngest is a three-month-old baby and the oldest is 110 years," said Health CS Mutahi Kagwe in a statement. The new cases were distributed across various counties as follows: Nairobi 719, Kitui 647, Siaya 105, Nakuru 95, Kericho 76, Kakamega 68, Mombasa 66, Uasin Gishu 65, Kiambu 61, Murang’a 52, Nyeri 51, Embu 41, Busia 34, Machakos 32, Makueni 31, Kirinyaga 28, Kisumu 28, Baringo 27, Kajiado 24, Kilifi 17, Trans Nzoia 17, Narok 16, Kwale 15, Taita Taveta 15, Homa Bay 12, Nyandarua 11, Bungoma 10, Bomet 9, Elgeyo Marakwet 9, Garissa 9, Nandi 9, Migori 8, Nyamira 7, Meru 6, Turkana 5, West Pokot 5, Isiolo 4, Kisii 4, Vihiga 3, Lamu 2 and Laikipia 1. The ministry noted that 1,066 patients recovered from the coronavirus; 1,016 from the Home-Based Isolation and Care program while 50 were discharged from various health facilities countrywide. Total recoveries stand at 262,133. However, 14 patients succumbed to the disease, one of them recorded in the last 24 hours and the rest being late deaths reported after conducting facility record audits. This pushes the cumulative fatalities to 5,425. “A total of 1,208 patients are currently admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 26, 324 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program,” added CS Kagwe. “46 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU), 25 of them on ventilatory support while 20 are on supplemental oxygen.” The CS added: “Another 331 patients are on supplemental oxygen and 303 of them are in the general wards. 28 patients are in the High Dependency Unit (HDU).” According to the Ministry, a total of 10,473,483 vaccines had been administered across the country as of January 6, 2022. Of these, 5,996,874  are partially vaccinated while those fully vaccinated are 4,412,786. The uptake of the second dose among those who received their first dose was at 56.5%.